        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will assign baseband 1 to C18O and SO, baseband 2 to 13CO, and the other two basebands to the continuum emission. For basebands assigned to the lines the 468.75 MHz bandwidth and 3840 channel mode is adopted, and to lower the data rate below the specified limit 2 and 4 channel averagings to the C18O and SO spectral data are adopted. This setting results in the spectral resolutions of 0.385 km s-1, 0.332 km s-1, and 0.661 km s-1 for the C18O, 13CO, and the SO lines, respectively. The velocity resolutions of the C18O and 13CO lines are high enough to investigate the kinematics of the envelope with the velocity width of ~4 km s-1, as demonstrated by our observing simulations (Figures 3 and 4). For the SO line we will investigate whether ringlike SO emission distribution in the transitional region between the envelope and disk is present or not, and the velocity resolution of 0.661 km s-1 is sufficient.

For the continuum basebands, the maximum bandwidth of 1.75 GHz will be adopted.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to image the entire protostellar envelope surrounding HL Tau. The combined interferometric + single-dish image of the 13CO (1-0) line in HL Tau exhibits a ~20 arcsec scale elongated envelope (Welch et al. 2000). Since the field of view of the 12-m array at Band 6 barely covers the entire envelope extent, we will perform 7-point mosaic observations with the 12-m array. The ACA 7-m and TP will supplement missing short spacing information, and we will be able to obtain high spatial dynamic images of HL Tau from 0.7 to ~20 arcsec scales. As demonstrated by our simulations shown in Figures 3 and 4, with this wide spatial coverage we should be able to investigate the kinematics of the ~3000 AU scale envelope and the transition from the envelope motion to the inner disk motion at a radius of ~100 AU.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our SMA image of the C18O (2-1) line in HL Tau shows the peak C18O (2-1) intensity of 0.41 Jy per 1.05 x 0.88 arcsec beam. Assuming the uniform flux distribution within the SMA beam, the expected flux within the ALMA beam of 0.70 x 0.65 arcsec is 0.20 Jy. To study the gas motions in detail, we aim to detect this peak C18O emission above &gt;25 sigma. With one execution of the Scheduling Block of the 12-m array we can achieve an rms noise level of 7 mJy / 0.385 km s-1, thus 28 sigma detection. We have constructed simple envelope models with the C18O flux after the spatial filtering of the SMA observation consistent with the real value. Then 12-m array, ACA 7-m, and TP observing simulations with the integration times and the number of pointings calculated by OT were performed. As shown in Figures 3 and 4, our simulations verify that with the rms noise level of 7 mJy and a velocity resolution of 0.385 km s-1 we can study the kinematics of the envelope / disk with the velocity width of ~4 km s-1 unambiguously.

The peak fluxes of the 13CO 2-1 and SO lines observed with the SMA are 1.6 and 2.0 times higher than the C18O peak flux, and these lines should be easily detectable.

The continuum emission in HL Tau is intense, and the peak 1.3-mm continuum flux derived with our SMA observation is 0.45 Jy / 1.00 x 0.83 arcsec ~0.25 Jy within the ALMA beam. The continuum detection level is as high as 4900 sigma.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
