            <prj:justificationText>We will assign baseband 1 to HCN (1-0), 2 to HCO+ (1-0), 3 to SO (3_2-2_1) and 4 to SO (4_5-4_4). The 117.188 MHz bandwidth mode is adopted for the HCN and HCO+ lines, and 468.750 MHz mode for the SO lines. To lower the data rate below the specified limit 2 channel averagings to the HCN and HCO+ data and 4 channel averagings to the SO data are adopted. This setting results in the spectral resolutions of 0.24 km s-1, 0.24 km s-1, and 1.46 km s-1 for the HCN, HCO+, and the SO lines, respectively. The velocity resolutions of the HCN and HCO+ lines are high enough to investigate the kinematics of the envelope with the velocity width of ~4 km s-1. For the SO lines we aim to detect the emission originated from the accretion shock at the transitional region from the envelope to the disk and to study the physical condition, not the detailed velocity structure. For the continuum emission, the ``aggregate'' bandwidth of 1.172 GHz will be adopted.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to image the entire protostellar envelope surrounding HL Tau. The combined interferometric + single-dish image of the 13CO (1-0) line in HL Tau exhibits a ~20 arcsec scale elongated envelope (Welch et al. 2000), and to cover the entire envelope extent the mapping region of 30"x30" is desirable. The field of view of the 12-m array at Band 3 well covers this region, and OT suggests no mosaic and no ACA. Since the ALMA long baseline data at Band 3 sample the spatial extent up to ~2", we aim to sample the spatial scale from ~2" to ~20".</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The ALMA long-baseline campaign data and the uv tapering show that the peak HCO+ (1-0) and HCN (1-0) intensities outside of the disk region are ~24 mJy/1.05"x0.95" (TB=3.7 K) and 12 mJy/1.04"x0.94" (1.9 K), respectively. Assuming the same brightness temperature in the extended components, the HCO+ and HCN fluxes within the proposed 2" beam are 96 mJy and 51 mJy, respectively. To study the gas motions in detail, we aim to detect this peak HCO+ emission above &gt;~20 sigma, thus rms~5 mJy. With just one execution of the Scheduling Block of the 12-m array (total observing time of 1.27 h) we can achieve an rms noise level of 5 mJy at a velocity resolution of 0.24 km s-1. The velocity resolution is high enough to study the kinematics of the envelope with the velocity width of ~4 km s-1.

There is no available data of the proposed Band 3 SO lines. If we assume that the brightness temperature of these lower excitation SO emission lines are a factor 2 lower than that of the proposed Band 6 SO line, the expected SO intensity is ~80 mJy/2.0", so should be detectable.

The ALMA long baseline data show that the 2.9-mm continuum emission at the edge of the disk region (r~0.7") is ~0.6 mJy / 0.085"x0.061" ~460 mJy /2" (assuming the same TB), and thus the continuum detection level is as high as 11800 sigma.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
